<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Lolium perenne </i>is a non-native grass from Europe, introduced into temperate regions throughout the world. It is an annual or a perennial, cool-season bunch grass with erect to decumbent culms and a fibrous root system that extends over 1 m deep. Animals disperse the abundant seed. Seeds germinate without stratification, and germination rates are > 70%. The seed bank is transient. Some plants produce tillers profusely (Carey 1995c, Sullivan 1992b). <br/>
<br/>
Some botanists treat the two forms of <i>L. perenne, </i>annual plants (ssp. <i>multiflorum</i>) and perennial plants (ssp. <i>perenne</i>), as separate species (Hickman 1993). Field identification is unreliable at the infraspecific level (Welsh et al. 1993). Plants do not appear strictly annual or perennial, and their culm height, degree of tiller development, and awn characters vary greatly, even within the same population. Most vegetation studies in California treat the plants as annuals. In botanical literature, this species is regularly referred to as <i>Festuca perennis</i>.<br/>
<br/>
<i>Lolium perenne </i>is a widespread and adaptable grass in cismontane California, and plants grow in a wide range of soil types, except for those excessively drained. Many herbaceous alliances have significant cover of <i>L. perenne, </i>including stands of the <i>Eleocharis macrostachya, Juncus arcticus</i> (var. <i>balticus, mexicanus</i>), <i>Leymus cinereus -  Leymus triticoides, Muhlenbergia rigens, Plagiobothrys nothofulvus, </i>and <i>Trifolium variegatum </i>alliances. While membership rules vary among studies, we consider that stands should have <i>L. perenne </i>as a strong dominant alone or with other non-natives, largely to the exclusion of native plants to be included in this type. Generally, this type occurs in seasonally moist to wet environments that are regularly disturbed through grazing, fire, flooding, or mechanical means. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
