    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of Lolium perenne includes all sections across cismontane California.</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aa, Af-g, Ak). Stands of <i>Lolium perenne </i>appear to have replaced native stands of <i>Juncus effusus, J.</i> (<i>oxymeris, xiphioides</i>), <i>Nassella pulchra, Leymus triticoides, Trifolium variegatum, </i>or other herbaceous alliances (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2007). Stands associated with springs of the East Bay Hills in Contra Costa Co. (Allen-Diaz et al. 2001) are grazed.</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Aa-k). Nitrogen deposition has assisted (Weiss 1999) in replacement of native stands on serpentine at Coyote Ridge in Santa Clara Co. (Evens and San 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Aa, Ac, Af-g, Ai-m, At). Stands of the Sacramento-San Joaquin delta include grazed pastures adjacent to vernal pools (Hickson and Keeler-Wolf 2007). Stands at Suisun Marsh (Keeler-Wolf and Vaghti 2000) are common in winter-flooded or saturated soils. They appear seral to stands of the <i>Atriplex lentiformis, Baccharis pilularis, Frankenia salina, </i>and <i>Sarcocornia pacifica</i> (<i>Salicornia depressa</i>) alliances. Stands with high <i>Lotus corniculatus, </i>included by Keeler-Wolf and Vaghti in a <i>Lotus corniculatus </i>alliance, have replaced native stands of <i>Leymus triticoides </i>in portions of the marsh. These related <i>Lotus </i>stands are included in this <i>Lolium perenne </i>description.</li>
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Gi). A single stand was surveyed at the far northern edge of this subsection, surrounded by grazed pasture. This stand was dominated by <i>Lotus corniculatus</i> (Boul et al. 2021b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Ac, Ae, Ag, Aj-m). Some stands at Humboldt Bay National Wildlife Refuge (Pickart 2006) include a high cover of <i>Lotus corniculatus</i>.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northwestern Basin and Range</b> (342Bd). One stand mapped at the southern edge of Bull Flat (Boul et al. 2021b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fa-e). Mesic upland stands exist at Peoria Wildlife Area (Evens et al. 2004) and those in the northern foothills (Klein et al. 2007) include natives such as <i>Centaurium muehlenbergii </i>or <i>Zigadenus fremontii.</i></li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-j). Mesic upland stands exist at Santa Monica Mountains (Keeler-Wolf and Evens 2006) and on Santa Cruz and San Nicolas Islands (Junak et al. 2007).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Lolium perenne </i>is an important forage crop for livestock but less used by wildlife. Managers have used it for erosion control, especially following fires, and as a winter cover crop. However, it is not effective at controlling erosion during the first year after a fire and may even increase erosion in succeeding years. It also competes with native plants and may increase the fire hazard in succeeding years (Carey 1995c, Sullivan 1992b). In addition, <i>L. perenne </i>establishes strongly on nutrient-poor soils, such as serpentine, when nitrogen deposition occurs from air pollution (Hopkinson et al. 2008, Weiss 1999). </div>
</div>

    

    

